Tips and tricks as a software developer for :
1- taking of the eyes
2- healthy body 
--------------------------
1- Taking breaks for the eyes:

Take regular breaks every 20-30 minutes, look away from the computer screen, and focus on something distant for at least 20 seconds.
Adjust your monitor's brightness and contrast to reduce eye strain.
Use the 20-20-20 rule: every 20 minutes, look at something at least 20 feet away for at least 20 seconds.

2- Maintaining a healthy body:

Take regular breaks to stand up and move around.
Incorporate stretching and exercises into your daily routine.
Try to maintain a healthy diet and get enough sleep.
Consider using a standing desk or an adjustable chair to reduce pressure on the back and neck.
Regularly check your posture and make necessary adjustments.
--------------------------
How to meditate as a software developer 

--------------------------
Meditation can be a helpful tool for software developers to reduce stress and improve focus. Here are a few tips for getting started with meditation:

Find a quiet, comfortable place to sit where you will not be disturbed.

Set a timer for a specific amount of time (e.g. 5-10 minutes) to start with.

Sit comfortably with your back straight, either on a chair or on the floor.

Close your eyes and focus on your breath.

When your mind wanders, gently bring your focus back to your breath.

Continue this process for the duration of your meditation session.

As you become more comfortable with meditation, you can increase the duration of your sessions or try different techniques, such as guided meditations or mindfulness practices.

It's important to be patient with yourself and not get discouraged if you find it difficult to quiet your mind at first. Meditation is a skill that takes time and practice to develop.

Make it a daily habit and be consistent with it, you can make it a part of your morning routine or evening routine whatever suits you better.

Be kind to yourself and remember that it's okay to have a busy mind, it's a normal thing and it's not a failure.